Great that you asked this, Abhishek üëç because this is a classic real-world scenario interview question. Let me explain step by step in super easy words how Authorization works in your Buy & Sale Property Application.

1Ô∏è‚É£ First Step ‚Äì Authentication (Who are you?)
When the user logs in (Buyer, Seller, or Admin), they enter username + password.
The backend checks in the database if the credentials are correct.
If correct, the backend issues a JWT Token that contains user info + role (Buyer, Seller, Admin).
üëâ Example of JWT payload:

{
  "id": 101,
  "username": "abhishek",
  "role": "Admin",
  "exp": 1736022000
}
2Ô∏è‚É£ Second Step ‚Äì Token Sent with Requests
Every time the frontend (Angular) calls an API (like /properties, /transactions), it attaches the JWT token in the request header:
Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1...
3Ô∏è‚É£ Third Step ‚Äì Authorization (What can you do?)
Now the backend checks the role inside the token.
Based on the role, it allows or denies access.
üëâ Example in .NET Core API:

[Authorize(Roles = "Admin")]
[HttpPost("approve-property")]
public IActionResult ApproveProperty(int propertyId)
{
    // Only admin can approve properties
    return Ok("Property approved!");
}

[Authorize(Roles = "Seller")]
[HttpPost("add-property")]
public IActionResult AddProperty(Property property)
{
    // Only sellers can add property
    return Ok("Property added!");
}

[Authorize(Roles = "Buyer,Seller")]
[HttpGet("view-properties")]
public IActionResult GetProperties()
{
    // Both buyers and sellers can view properties
    return Ok();
}
4Ô∏è‚É£ Example Flow in Your App
Buyer logs in ‚Üí gets token with role = "Buyer".
They can search, view properties, chat with sellers, but cannot approve or reject listings.
Seller logs in ‚Üí gets token with role = "Seller".
They can add new property, update price, but cannot view payment reports.
Admin logs in ‚Üí gets token with role = "Admin".
They can approve/reject properties, manage users, view reports.
üéØ Interview-Friendly Short Answer
üëâ ‚ÄúIn my property buy/sell app, we use JWT Authentication to identify the user. The JWT contains the role (Buyer, Seller, Admin). On each API call, the backend checks this role and applies [Authorize(Roles="...")].
This way, the application knows who the user is and what they are allowed to do. For example, only admins can approve listings, only sellers can add properties, and buyers can only view and purchase properties.‚Äù

Would you like me to also show you step-by-step Angular code (like how you store the JWT in localStorage and check role in guards for routing)? That‚Äôs another interview follow-up they usually ask.


//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////State Management

Great question, Abhishek üëç because state management comes up a lot in interviews when they want to test whether you understand how web applications keep track of user data between requests.


---

üåç First, Why State Management?

HTTP is stateless ‚Üí every request from the client to the server is independent.

That means, by default, the server doesn‚Äôt remember who you are between two requests.


üëâ Example: You log in ‚Üí request is done ‚Üí on the next request, server doesn‚Äôt know you‚Äôre logged in unless you manage state.

So, State Management = techniques to store and retrieve user/session data across requests.


---

üèóÔ∏è State Management in ASP.NET Core

1. Client-Side State Management

Data is stored on the client (browser).

Examples:

Cookies ‚Äì small data stored in browser, can persist even after closing the browser.

Response.Cookies.Append("UserRole", "Admin");

Local Storage / Session Storage (Angular/JS) ‚Äì used to store JWT tokens, user info.

Hidden Fields in forms.



‚úÖ Advantage: reduces server load.
‚ùå Disadvantage: can be tampered if not encrypted.


---

2. Server-Side State Management

Data is stored on the server.

Examples:

Session State

Stores data per user session on the server.

Works using a cookie (Session ID) to identify the session.


HttpContext.Session.SetString("UserRole", "Admin");
var role = HttpContext.Session.GetString("UserRole");

Cache / MemoryCache / Distributed Cache

Store frequently used data to improve performance.

Distributed cache (like Redis, SQL Server) is used in load-balanced apps.


services.AddDistributedMemoryCache();
services.AddSession();



‚úÖ Advantage: safer, more control.
‚ùå Disadvantage: consumes server memory.


---

3. Token-Based State (Modern Approach)

Instead of session storage, in modern apps we often use JWT tokens.

The token contains the state (user id, roles, expiry) and is stored client-side.

Server doesn‚Äôt store session data, just validates the token with a secret key.


‚úÖ Advantage: scalable, no server memory usage.
‚ùå Disadvantage: Token size can grow, needs refresh token strategy.


---

üéØ Interview-Friendly Answer

üëâ ‚ÄúState management in .NET Core means maintaining user data across multiple requests because HTTP is stateless.
We can manage state client-side using cookies, local storage, or hidden fields, and server-side using session state, cache, or distributed cache.
In modern apps, I mostly use JWT token-based state management, where the token carries user info like ID and roles, and the server validates it on each request.
For example, in my property app, once a user logs in, we issue a JWT token stored in localStorage. The backend extracts the user‚Äôs role from the token to handle authorization.‚Äù


---

‚ö°Abhishek, do you want me to also prepare scenario-based cross-questions that interviewers might ask on state management (like Session vs JWT, when to use Cache, etc.)?


