////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Rank and RowNumber.
Excellent question, Abhishek üëè

Let‚Äôs break this down in super easy words so that even a 10-year-old can understand it perfectly ‚Äî and it‚Äôs interview-ready too.

üß© Definition (Easy Words)
üëâ ROW_NUMBER()

Gives a unique number to each row ‚Äî 1, 2, 3, 4, ‚Ä¶
Even if two rows have the same value, they get different numbers.
Think of it like giving roll numbers to students ‚Äî even if marks are the same, roll numbers are unique.
üëâ RANK()

Also gives numbers based on sorting order,
But if two rows have the same value, they get the same rank, and the next rank is skipped.
Think of it like Olympic medals ‚Äî if two players tie for 1st place, the next one is 3rd (2nd is skipped).
üßÆ Example
SELECT 
    Name, 
    Marks,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY Marks DESC) AS RowNum,
    RANK() OVER (ORDER BY Marks DESC) AS RankNum
FROM Students;
Suppose the table looks like this:
Name	Marks
A	95
B	90
C	90
D	85
Output:
Name	Marks	RowNum	RankNum
A	95	1	1
B	90	2	2
C	90	3	2
D	85	4	4
‚úÖ ROW_NUMBER() ‚Üí Always unique (1, 2, 3, 4)
‚úÖ RANK() ‚Üí Same rank for same marks, and skips the next number (1, 2, 2, 4)

üèó Project Use (Buy & Sell Property App)
In your Buy & Sell Property Application,
you can use RANK() or ROW_NUMBER() for features like:

Ranking properties based on price or rating.
e.g., RANK() OVER (ORDER BY Price DESC) ‚Üí helps show ‚ÄúTop 10 most expensive properties.‚Äù
Showing unique numbers to each property in a search result using ROW_NUMBER().
‚öñÔ∏è Trade-offs
Case	When to Use
üßÆ ROW_NUMBER()	When you just want unique numbering, no skips.
üèÜ RANK()	When you want to show equal rank for same values.
üíº Business Impact
Helps users easily view sorted and ranked data (like Top Properties, Top Sellers).
Improves data presentation and analytics, which helps business users take decisions faster.
